# file containing location info and ISO code for a lot of the world's cities
city_location = pd.read_csv('worldcities.csv')
city_location = city_location[['city', 'lat', 'lng', 'country', 'iso2']]

# ISO code for only european countries
iso2_eu = {'AD','AL','AM','AT','BA','BE','BG','BY','CH','CY','CZ','DE','DK','EE','ES','FI','FO','FR','GB','GE','GI','GR','HR','HU','IE','IM','IS','IT','LI','LT','LU','LV','MC','MD','ME','MK','MT','NL','NO','PL','PT','RO','RS','RU','SE','SI','SK','SM','TR','UA','VA','XK'}

# we discard non-European cities
city_location_eu = city_location.loc[city_location["iso2"].isin(iso2_eu)]
for column in ['city']:
    city_location_eu[column] = city_location_eu[column].str.lower()

Visualization 1: dot distribution map, colored by receiving/sending ratio¶

In [ ]:
# Create a dictionary to count the occurrences of each city in 'sending' and 'receiving'
city_counts = {}

for index, row in euromob2.iterrows():
    sending_city = row['Sending City']
    receiving_city = row['Receiving City']

    if sending_city in city_counts:
        city_counts[sending_city][0] += 1
    else:
        city_counts[sending_city] = [1, 0]

    if receiving_city in city_counts:
        city_counts[receiving_city][1] += 1
    else:
        city_counts[receiving_city] = [0, 1]

# Create the final dictionary with the desired values
result_dict = {}

for index, row in euromob_cities.iterrows():
    city = row['city']
    sending_count, receiving_count = city_counts.get(city, [0, 0])

    if sending_count > 0:
        ratio = receiving_count / sending_count
    else:
        ratio = 0

    result_dict[city] = [sending_count, receiving_count, ratio]
In [33]:
# just to be sure: check again and discard cities with no mobilities
to_delete = set()
for city,info in result_dict.items():
    if info[0]==0 and info[1]==0:
        to_delete.add(city)

for k in to_delete:
    result_dict.pop(k, None)
    
for key in sorted(result_dict)[:10]:
    print(key, result_dict[key])

'''
There are cities with anomalously high ratios (over 100, when most remain below 30), so we will discard them to enhance our visualization
By using percentiles, we will ensure most of our data remains while discarding the cases mentioned.

'''

# Get statistics on the 'mobilities_count' column
ratio_stats = result_df['ratio'].describe()
mean, maximum = ratio_stats[1], ratio_stats[-1]
print(f'ratio stats:\n mean: {mean}\n max: {maximum}\n')

# Computing percentile values for 'mobilities_count' column
lower_value = result_df['ratio'].quantile(0.1)
upper_value = result_df['ratio'].quantile(0.99)

print(f'Only cities with ratios between {lower_value} and {upper_value} will remain.')

# Filtering rows within the specified percentile range
result_df2 = result_df[
    (result_df['ratio'] >= lower_value) &
    (result_df['ratio'] <= upper_value)]

ratio_stats2 = result_df2['ratio'].describe()
mean2, maximum2 = ratio_stats2[1], ratio_stats2[-1]
print(f'ratio stats:\n mean: {mean2}\n max: {maximum2}\n')

# COUNTING MOBILITIES BETWEEN CITIES

euromob3 = euromob2.rename(columns={
    'Sending City': 'sending_city',
    'Receiving City': 'receiving_city'
})


# Grouping by 'sending_city' and 'receiving_city' and counting occurrences
mobilities_count = euromob3.groupby(['sending_city', 'receiving_city']).size()

# To avoid pandas error message
euromob3.name = 'euromob3'
mobilities_count.name = 'mobilities_count'

# Merging the counts back into the original DataFrame
euromob3 = pd.merge(euromob3, mobilities_count, on=['sending_city', 'receiving_city'], how='left')

euromob3

In [24]:
'''
To enhance our visualization, we will only show the most relevant mobilities, meaning those that
appear the most (a setting in the map visualization will allow the user to filter mobilities through
a count range slider). To capture them, we will make use of percentiles.

'''

# Get statistics on the 'mobilities_count' column
mobilities_stats = euromob4['mobilities_count'].describe()
mean, maximum = mobilities_stats[1], mobilities_stats[-1]
print(f'mobilities_count stats:\n mean: {mean}\n max: {maximum}\n')

# Dropping row with maximum value in 'mobilities_count', because it is probably anomalous data
euromob5 = euromob4
euromob5 = euromob5[euromob5['mobilities_count'] != maximum]

# Computing percentile values for 'mobilities_count' column
lower_value = euromob5['mobilities_count'].quantile(0.98)  # avoid mobilities that are too infrequent
upper_value = euromob5['mobilities_count'].quantile(0.999) # avoid mobilities that are way too frequent (anomalous)

# Filtering rows within the specified percentile range
euromob5 = euromob5[
    (euromob5['mobilities_count'] >= lower_value) &
    (euromob5['mobilities_count'] <= upper_value)]

euromob5
